Yet another copter. This time with 5 motors. The desing is base on delta style tricopter. Advantages:
  • Nice flight control with tricopter style yaw authority
  • Lot of thrust (5 motors give extrea power)
  • The shape allows to see copter orientation from long distance

To be printed:
  • 1x side base
  • 1x mirrored side base
  • 1x bridge
  • 2x motor spacers
  • 1x tail base
  • 1x tail motor part
  • 1x upper deck
    • Other material
  • vibration dampers (4 pcs)
  • motors for 250 size racing quads (5 pcs) (such as DYS BE1806 2300KV)
  • 15A ESC (5pcs) (such as AfroSlim)
  • 9g servo (metal gear)
  • control board
  • 6 inch props (6030)
  • R/C transmitter and receiver
  • Battery (such as ZippyCompact 2200mAh) - check dimensions. It has to fit bellow main deck
    • Assembly
  • put side bases on flat surface and join them using bridge. Put a bit of hot glue into contact zone. Use zip tie to secure assembly (run it trough the bridge and both base parts)
  • install servo into tail part (do not forget to get it centered)
  • install tail motor part (2 mm dia axis 10-15 mm length on both sides is fine)
  • fix servo arm to tail motor part (to the flap)
  • join tail part with side bases. Put a bit of hot glue into contact zone. Use zip tie to secure assembly (run it trough the tail and base part)

description.text: The original version wasn't printing nicely on my M3D, the eyes were hard to see and the hook on the top right wasn't rigid enough.

I really like to tinker with an Arduino Nano (or one its many compatibles), since it provides the same functionality as the Uno, but on a much smaller footprint. However, what I like less are the vertical pins underneath the PCB, since they are exposed to the working desk and are therefore prone for wrong contacts and even shorting due to tools or other metallic items on the desk. Also, since the leads are attached to the lower side of the PCB, it is difficult to keep the Nano upright, so that the pin labels and LED indicators on the top side stay visible. So this project presents a way to overcome these difficulties by making all pin connections horizontal and providing a shell around the Nano which protects all pins from accidental exposure and keeps the Nano in a stable horizontal position. Right angle pin headers mounted on the upper side of the Nano PCB are used instead of the straight headers normally used. Two 15-pin single row and one 3x2-pin double row pin header arrays are needed. This way, all connections to he Nano are horizontal and are safely "hidden" between the upper and lower part of the shell. The so covered horizontal pin connectors increase the surface of the Nano shell, so that there is enough space for attaching a sticker on the top shell which identifies each pin in a nicely readable size. The top of the shell has a cutout for the 4 LEDs and has an integrated RESET button which is printed in-situ and held in position by its waisted shape. Given that there are several variants of the Nano design which essentially differ slightly in the placement of the LEDs and the RESET button, so their longitudinal position is parametrized (ledy and resety, measured in mm from the USB end of the PCB) and can thus be easily adapted when needed. In addition to this SCAD file, there is also a corresponding PostScript file which generates the labels to stick on the top part of the shell. It, too, is configurable for the exact position of the RESET button and the LEDs (using again the same variables ledy and resety) Ready-to-print STL files (3D-printing of the Nano shell) and PDF files (2D printing of the label stickers) are provided for the 3 main variants of the Nano:
  • Original Arduino Nano: ledy=29mm, resety=24mm, LED order is "TX RX PWR D13"
  • "Baite" Compatible: ledy=30mm, resety=25mm, LED order is "D13 PWR RX TX"
  • "New" Nano 3.0 Compatible with small LED spacing: ledy=32mm, resety=26mm, LED order is "TX RX PWR D13"
    • Measure the distances of LEDs and Reset button from the USB end of the PCB and print out the corresponding STL and PDF files, or modify the SCAD and PS sources accordingly. Update 2015-07-21: I have now uploaded an improved version of the Nano Pin Protector which contains air flow windows underneath the lateral pins in order to improve the air flow below the Nano PCB. I have also added a new variant with ledy=33 and resety=27, which gives a better fit on some Nano versions. Update 2015-08-14: If you are interested in using a much more powerful 32-bit micro-controller board with about the same size, price and Arduino-IDE as the Nano, then check out my new Maple Mini Pin Protector.

The Nano protector shells were printed from 3mm ABS filament on my DIY Prusa i3 using a 0.4mm nozzle with 0.56mm extrusion width and 0.252 layer height. I print on a clear mirror without Kapton tape but thoroughly cleaned with acetone and double concentrated lemon juice.   
Since the two parts of the protective shell hold to each other by a "click"-type mechanism, ABS seems to be the material of choice for this project.

Tip out tray for hinged sink door storage. 6/15/15: Added Larger version Small version is: 7" wide, 2" standout from door, and 2.75" high.
Large version is: 8.75" wide, 2: stand out from door, and 3.25 high. If you want a tip-out tray and have plastic to burn, these are nice ones. Most tip out sink doors will support two of these side by side. I'm thinking instead of using 4 screws, I'll super glue the joining sides and glue a plastic bar across the bottom, which effectively makes it one piece with a divider in the middle. Plus only need 2 screws this way. NOTE: I designed this from a solid block, from which material was removed. Also note that the large version still shows holes in the back. I left the pattern but closed the holes so moisture wouldn't get on the mounted surface. The large tray didn't update, so I made a v2 for no holes in the back. Left the other one just in case someone prefers the holes.

My first print was ABS, but it pulled up from glass some, maybe the print bed wasn't hot enough, but I'll try PLA on the next one.  
The larger tray pushes the limits of the Flashforge Creator.  I printed the first couple layers and it will do fine.

This is a wall-based spool mount that uses only printed parts. No dowels or rods required - just mounting hardware.  
The clips were derived from Logan's "Spool Hanger Bracket" on Thingiverse. I added an additional chamfered hole for fastening below the clip for more secure mounting.  
The bar that goes through the spool has a flat bottom for easy printing and a rounded top for easy spinning. The asymmetric design also means that the bar snaps nicely into the clips. The square ends are there to prevent it from slipping out just in case.  
The wall mount ensures that the clips are mounted at the correct pitch. The hole in the middle allows for a slightly larger spool without longer clips, and saves on filament.  
Use anchors or wood screws as appropriate for mounting to your wall.

Print one bar, two clips, and one plate in the as-rendered orientations. 25% infill provides sufficient stiffness for holding up 1 kg spools of PLA.  
FYI, I used 0.4 mm layer height Diamond Age PLA on a Printbot LC with a heated glass bed (185C/60C) and had absolutely no issues.

description.text:
NOTICE: I feel this design is now out of date and there are many things I would have done differently designing it. It does work, however the stress distribution is not very well thought out and there isn't a lot of space to mount components. I am working on a new carbon tube based design which I hope to release in a few months, in an "H" configuration, clamped with 3D printed components, and specialized for lightweight aerial photography. Hope you all will enjoy it! The Skyblade frame is designed for strength and printability (especially for the Printrbot Simple Metal) from the start. I've built upon other designs which I have seen on Thingiverse to to create a base for an easy to build and fly drone. This frame can be completely assembled with zip ties, (I know you're thinking that's not very sturdy) but it feels very stiff and and I have had no structural integrity issues. There is enough clearance between each of the arms for 10" blades. I am using 10" and it feels very responsive and stable, but it also has a lot of power for some fun as well! It is very quiet with the components I use, I believe this is due to the Sunnysky motors. I have had no speed controller oscillation issues which many people complain about, but the Afro 30A ESCs seem to be very good. It has mounting holes for:
-CC3D Flight Controller
-Hobbyking Actioncam Gimbal
-Hobbyking Bullet Connector Power Distribution Board
-SunnySky X2212 KV980 II Motors Please check out my blog for parts list and building steps:
https://timelapse21.wordpress.com/2015/06/14/skyblade-v1-0-parts-and-assembly-tips-2/ Designed Using Fusion360
Please go to https://timelapse21.wordpress.com/2015/06/14/skyblade-v1-0-parts-and-assembly-tips-2/

comments.text: Didn't design it for those motors, you'd have to design some new arms. Sorry! I gave up on this design and am working on a new design with carbon fibre tubes which is a bit larger and easier to mount stuff on if you are interested in waiting for that, but there are a bunch of other good designs on thingiverse too. I tend to focus on designing just for the electronics I have.
comments.author: pjkuras

comments.text: Was this setup for fpv?
comments.author: greasemonkeynola

comments.text: Not really, more just for practicing flying within eyesight.
comments.author: greasemonkeynola

comments.text: Hi! Thanks for the build.. I noticed on your website you do not specify what battery you use and I can't tell from the pictures. If you could specify it would be great! Thanks!
comments.author: Arctic_Ox

comments.text:
I'm using a Zippy 5000mah from hobbyking, seems to work well and I get around 15 minute flight times. Here is a link:
http://www.hobbyking.com/hobbyking/store/__21370__ZIPPY_Compact_5000mAh_3S_25C_Lipo_Pack.html
I switched out the leads with XT-60 so it connects directly to the PDB. Good luck! If you need any more info you can let me know.
Could you post some pictures if you make one?
comments.author: Arctic_Ox

description.text:
I am experimenting a bit with how the Cap clips onto the Base. I am very open to suggestions on how to improve.  
I would recommend printing the "Base" in a flexible filament, and then scale it a bit down (0.9 - 0.95). The "Cap" and "Pin" is better printed in a harder material. If you want to print the base in a harder material as well, then leave the size.

comments.text: What is the inside diameter? Also, just an Idea for the ones wanting to have the auto open option. Hollow out the inside of the rod holes to be able to put a spring inside and widen the 2 side supports for the straight parts of the spring. Have a spring the looks like this "lool" and that should be able have it open automatically. Just an Idea.

A microswitch with a little roller or lever out the front is best.

description.text: I had just completed the Matrix Precision X,Y, and Z upgrade for my Printrbot Simple Metal and the provided extended legs to stabilize the longer Z travel was not printing correctly for me. It was not the model, it was just the way Cura was slicing it perhaps because the notches did not match what was in the model (although all other measurements did). Here is the link to Matrix Precision's model: http://www.matrix-precision.com/pages/downloads As such, I decided to make my own based on Matrix Precision's design but made a couple changes including making it slightly shorter and adding 0.5mm cant at the base of the feet to compensate for bending in the legs. As an aside, no matter how great of a design, I always found any legs or feet to be ineffective when your printer is on a glass table. It still jitterbugs all over the place. So I always put sugru on the base of the feet which you can see in the pics. Now the thing will not budge no matter what. I printed this fine at 0.2mm, 20% infill (this is risky - I would go higher), 70mm/s using plain-ol-black-1.75-pla. Hope you find it helpful!!

description.text: This derivation of the Airtripper Bowden extruder (version 3.0) centers more parts and holes and parameterizes filament size, tolerant at least between 1.75 and 3mm. Default settings are for a 3mm filament with an MK7 drive gear (10.56mm effective diameter). The Bowden tube outer diameter is presumed to be 6mm. The mounting holes are also parametric and are set up here with grooves for 3mm bolts, good for attachment to beam extrusions.

Currently still experimental. Adjust prior to printing to get your desired alignment.
  • Print the complete set of parts.
  • Add (1) 608ZZ bearing to the bearing holder.
  • Attach a drive gear (MK7 perhaps) to the motor shaft and align its grabby region with the filament guides.
  • Attach the strut and extruder body to a NEMA 17 motor with bolts: (1) M3x25mm, (2) M3x30mm, (1) M3x7mm.
  • Use (2) M3x30mm bolts with (2) M3 nuts to secure for the bearing holder. You could also use longer bolts with springs and washers.

author: m_zapp

description.text: twt

Combining the two of my newest hobbies; lockpicking and 3D modeling I thus present a simple pin tumbler lock model with a cut on the side for viewing / demonstrating the operation.  
This is just for demonstrating the operation and there is no latch in the end of the plug for actually connecting it to something or w/e. It can be picked, although I recommend using very light tension due to thin chamber sides on the open cut area. Also due to layers, all the pins act bit like serrated security pins unless you smooth them. :)  
I printed the plug and the housing from PLA with 0.2mm layer height, 10% infill and 2 perimeters and using slic3r automatic supports. Driver pins and key pins are best to be printed with thinner layers (0.1mm).  
Springs I took from ballpoint pens, cut one spring in half to get correct height springs for 2 chambers.  
No key provided, arrange the key pins however you like and make your own :)

UPDATE: Added block_cut_v1.1 and cylinder_cut_v1.1 which feature slightly thicker walls for the chambers in the cut area, that should improve the strength of the chamber walls and make printing easier.

Recommend using support for housing and the plug, depending on your printer you may/may not be able to print them without support too.  
Use small layer height for pins.  
Print 5 x driver pins and 5 x key pins (different heights provided).  
Ballpoint pen springs for driving the pins.

description.text:
A little mechanical toy i constructed based on a photo i have seen. All gaps are 0,2 mm wide. If you need bigger (or smaller) gaps write me a short message. I usually replay within a week ;-) Solidworks files are availble at request. You will need:
1 x "staender.STL" - its the base.
12 x "axis.stl"
12 x "Gear.stl"
5 x "knot.stl"
24 x screw M3, sinkhead x 20 mm (M3 x 30 will do als well) The way the knots are designed the base fitts in every hole (add pun here) - should work perfectly with 12 different colours. Or, if you are brave, print the "baum komplett.stl" - if you have a good printer the parts should be moving after printing.

This is a simple plastic thing to cover the hole in a patio table where an umbrella would go with a cover.  
The .stl is for a 52-56mm umbrella hole which is the standard size - at least here in the United States.   The top cover is 60mm in diameter across.  
If you want a smaller or larger cover, download the .scad file, download OpenSCAD and adjust the parameters per the comments in the file to be whatever measurements you want, and then Render and do File->Export to STL and print it.  If you've never done OpenSCAD before, this is a great simple example to show you how it works (the code is 5 lines long in total).
Sliced with Slicr with 0.3mm layer height and printed  on a Printrbot Simple Metal, with the top-cover side down in 22 minutes.

I broke my frame, and my friend Tony offered me to help design a new one (he was an eyewear designer for some years). That's not perfect yet, but it's already cool :) http://watsdesign.blogspot.com/2011/05/glasses-for-everyone-in-progress.html Ultimately I wish we could make a parametric design, maybe with a cool interface like magic-box:
http://magic-box.org/tool/?url=http://magic-box.org/designs/presentation/glasses.mbt&state=viewer And thus allowing almost everyone to make their own glasses in a fablab (a lasercutter is certainly better for this job).
In the same philosophy of these two other project:
http://www.thethirdteacher.com/ourvoice/march-12-2010-%E2%80%93-do-it-yourself-eye-exam/2010/03/12
http://fuseproject.com/category-6-product-45 But with more diy-open-source-freedom :) [edit 04 aug 2011:] Just discovered http://www.oyoglasses.com/ maybe they will allow mass-cutomization of 3d-printed glasses

Atm the frame will only fit one shape of lenses, so you must adapt it if you want to use it (unless you just want to wear a frame:p)
The first stl is quite tiny, the second a little bit thicker, and "lunettes manu" are those that I actually wear :D

comments.text: IÂ´m going to modify these for a broken pair of mine and I want to reuse the glasses in this new frame, but I got a few small questions: How do you fix the glasses inside, so that they are not going to fall out and has anybody tried to wear them for (at least) several days? I would like to know how they are for everyday life, e.g. when its cold outside or really hot during summer - i would build them with ABS and any new infos for this would be great.
comments.author: jo_hannes

comments.text: The glasses are supposed to be clipped but in the end I just glued them discretely. I was wearing them everyday for almost a year, I broke them twice but easily repaired, until a last accident I didn't spent the time to repair them again. I had to heat the frame with a lighter to really adapt the shape for the lenses and bend the branches ; they were also little too thick between the head and ear and tended to slip but still wearable :)
comments.author: jo_hannes

comments.text: The best way to attach the lenses is by making a groove in the edge of the lens and holding it with a tensioned nylon string. (this is how regular semi-rimless frames mount the lenses). All that's required is a ridge in the frame to go into the groove and a pair of holes at each sided of each lens to anchor the nylon to.

description.text: These parts are designed to work with joseph_terzian 's 3D Glasses Stand Samsung Smart TV (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:161737). Included is a base with tray for small items, clips to attach the base to the bottom of the glasses holder, and extended support rods for normal glasses.

Print 1 Base, 2 Clips, and as many Rods as you need. Insert the Base's pegs into the holes in the bottom-most glasses holder. Insert the clips in the square slots in the back of said holder (where the 1/4-20 nuts are designed to go. If the clips will not engage the pegs, try sanding the clips so their thickness will allow them to slide onto the pegs correctly. Add Rods to holders as needed and bond with adhesive or acetone slurry.

A customizable 3D printable piece that holds a Yagi Antenna together. This piece provides connection between metal rods that function as a dipole elements and a profile that holds all the rods together. A simple DIY Yagi Antenna design is available here: http://dk7zb.darc.de/Duoband/duoband_2-70_2-3.htm. The .stl files are available for a few dimensions. OpenSCAD source file is also available if you require any other dimension.
• any bolt that will connect rod, 3D printed piece and profile together

Blaz Bratus
Institute IRNAS Race
www.irnas.eu - www.facebook.com/instituteirnas - twitter.com/institute_irnas
Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike 4.0 International License

• Download the correct .stl file and print the piece / pieces.

  • If you require any other dimension, OpenSCAD source file is also available. It enables you to alter few key dimensions of the part.

description.text: This was created by using my cellphone camera and 123D Catch. Every year in the Cloverdale and Geyserville CA area over 30 sculptures are strategically placed in and around town. This is put on by the Cloverdale Arts Alliance and the Geyserville Community Foundation. Check them out here: http://101sculpturetrail.com. Having so many wonderful sculptures to choose from made it difficult to choose. Mr. Crompton's beautiful artistic style made the choice allot easier. you can see his work here: http://cromptondesign.com/crompton_design/home.html. I have printed my copy in PLA on my modified MakerBot 2X on high resolution with 10% infill and 2 shells. I also slowed it down about 20% and printed it at 150mm tall. I am entering this one into the #SeeTheWorld challenge.
Print on high resolution with 10% infill with supports. Unless you have adhesion issues, don't use a raft.  Save the plastic!

This is still a work in progress so be kind :) Ive wanted to make one of these for a long time and finally got around to modeling it and printing. The model was printed at 1:4 on a ProJet SD 3000. I am not sure how it will come out on other machines but it looks good coming from the ProJet. Just a warning the "claws" are very fragile so be careful and print a few extra! This is my first attempt so there will be changes in the near future:
-Claws are too thin, need to beef them up a bit
-Add built in battery compartment for LED lighting :)
-Work on spring mechanism for claws
-??? The STEP file is available here ( http://grabcad.com/library/portal-gun ). If you would like the SolidWorks model send me an email. Enjoy!
https://picasaweb.google.com/bruins.scott/PortalGun?feat=directlink
3D Print: !Warning! STL files are 1:1 will need to be scaled down.

I printed mine in blue ABS and painted it with acrylic paint and it looks great -- I just didn't have any black filament laying around.  
This is the first version, I'm still considering optimal size and shape, but it really makes vaping feel like you've got a pipe.  
I like to pop it on with the button facing either inward or forward.  Makes for easier use.  Enjoy!

This adaptor is for the Canon T4I, I custom designed it to fit my Meade telescope. I remove the eyepiece and connect it right into the telescope. The focus adjustment on the telescope was sufficient to get subjects in focus. I haven't had a chance to try it at night yet. Works on trees during the day.  
The OD of the eyepiece portion is roughly 1.25 inches, so it might work on other telescopes.  
Modeled in solidworks.

comments.text: Not bad...I flipped Y axis to print upside down to avoid overhang issues and having to remove excess supports.  But didn't realise when I did that it changed the direction of the Keys...Fortunately on the Eos it doesn't care about the direction that you turn it in...Phewwww.....
comments.author: lklmmedia

comments.text:
Made - Used - Happy:
I found I had to attached the Barlow though - as the focal point was about 4 inches further back than expected. The only problem with that is the camera weight then causes the barlow to tilt and the camera ends up offcentre. I might adjust original design to be as long as the barlow to make sure it is one piece but also have an outer sheath which goes around the inlet to allow using pushing adjustment screws to line it up.
Other than that - Very happy with the results against the Full moon tonight.
comments.author: lklmmedia

description.text:
SkyRod is a three games family. Clip the rod on the screen of your computer and hang three different objects to play three different games moving in front of your webcam. The game will be soon available on the website: http://skyrodgame.com
Here you can find the files to 3d print the rod, and the 3 game players: a plane, a stone and a cloud. For now, the rod I propose only fits with Macbook Pro Retina 15, but will be soon available for other formats and computer brands. Feel free to hack this project and make your own objects and rod to improve your experience.
SkyRod is my Diploma project for my Bachelor in Media Interaction Design studies in ECAL, Switzerland.

title: Dragon Head Mount for Raspberry Pi Camera

description.text:
This head was made as part of an ongoing robotics project.
I suspect it may be useful to other people so I'm uploading it separately.
Plus it's nice to show things off. There are holes for LEDs behind the eyes, so they light up. The head has 3 M5 holes in the base to attach the mount, along with 4 M2 holes inside the head to mount the camera to. The teeth partially occlude the camera vision, but not badly.
The extent of this is shown in the gallery.

LEDs are mounted in the top of the head, and held in place with contact adhesive.
Both LEDs are in series with a 50 Ohm resistor, and are connected in parallel between the ground and the 3V pin on the Pi. M2 shafts were used to join the different sections of the head. With the exception of the eyes, the exterior of the head was painted with several layers of Humbrol primer, and then painted with enamel paint. The eyes were varnished, and then had pupils painted on.

title: JFettig Machines Printable Mini Lathe CNC Conversion Hardware

description.text: http://www.jfettigmachines.com/ Ever since I got my CNC lathe, I've been wanting to convert the other mini lathe that's sitting idle. The JFettig design is as non-invasive as it gets. The parts are meant to be machined out of aluminum, but I think ABS will suffice for most light work. At the very least, it will give me a chance to test fit the conversion before commiting to geting metal parts made.

For those of you wanting to make this, please hold off for a few days, while I get myself organized, and post new files.  
I've re-designed the pieces to be more friendly to 3D printing, and more durable.  
The old BOM is no longer valid.

comments.text:
This made my day seeing this posted up. I designed these almost 10 years ago.
I took the main page down from my site but the plans are still there:
http://www.jfettigmachines.com/lathekit.html
comments.author: JFettig

comments.text: So funny, I came across someone mentioning your design on CNCzone and could not find the link just days ago!
comments.author: JFettig

comments.text: Wow!  I'm glad you found this.  I really liked this design.  Just last week I was showing the parts to an acquaintance that is looking to convert his mill. My lathe is still not done.  As I started taking it apart, I found some broken gears.  I got replacements, ut now I need to find the time.  Again...
comments.author: JFettig

comments.text: i am looking to add cnc to a 7x10 mini lathe..  what is this sized for?
comments.author: matt_o_70

comments.text: I've only seen the two model that Harbor Freight sells, which are 7x10 and 7x12 (I think), and it fits both of those.  Most other Chinese-made mini lathes are pretty much identical.  Let me add a couple of pictures for the mounting points, and you can take measurements to compare.  Essentially, you are replacing the X-axis knob, and the Y-axis threading movement.
comments.author: matt_o_70

comments.text: Yep I have the HF -  any suggestion for Approx Motor torque required for the steppers? I assume these are NEMA23's
comments.author: wildseyed

comments.text: Unlike CNC mills, lathes (of this size anyway) don't need much more than a light touch.  A medium torque single stack NEMA 23 should be fine.
comments.author: matt_o_70

comments.text: The nice thing about ABS is that you can lost 'wax' cast with it. I'm planning on building a lathe from scratch using printed parts then cast in aluminum.
comments.author: Tannius

author: janjo091

title: ELF Drone - Propeller cover (maybe call them drone stabilisers)

description.text:
I backed the 3D printed drone on Indigogo (https://www.indiegogo.com/projects/elf-the-hd-video-streaming-nano-drone/x/7648351#/story) but I've never owned a drone before so was a little concerned about smashing it in to things and both damaging them and the drone it's self. So I thought I'd create some removable stabilisers. This is the first time I've ever created anything in 3D so I'm not sure if these can be printed yet. I have a feeling there might be problems due to some of the angles but once my printer arrives I'll see how it works and iterate the design. The Drone:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:877290

title: Case for DSO 062 JYE Tech Oscilloscope

description.text:
This is an inspired mashup from a couple things noted below, but made to fit my JYE Tech DSO 062. Redrawn from scratch.  
You can pick from a plain bottom or one with a kickstand. To attach the kickstand, insert a piece of 1.75mm filament for a hinge pin. On mine the filament fit well, but there's room for a spot of glue inside if you need it.

• Print it !
  • Slip the kickstand into the slots in the bottom if you opt for it.
  • Slide a 1" or so long piece of filament through the hinge pin holes for the kickstand to pivot on.
  • Remove the bottom PCB cover plate from your DSO 062 and keep it for a cold beverage coaster from now on.
    Feel free to take a sip at this point.
  • Replace the PCB bottom plate with the bottom half of the case, using the same 4 screws to fix it into position.
  • Remove the top plate of your DSO 062 and keep it nearby.
  • Slip the top of the case into position.
  • Screw the top plate back onto your DSO 062. This clamps the top of the case to the bottom, and you're done.
    A tidy DSO sandwich to go with your drink.

description.text:
Adapter for fitting a 3.5" device in a 5.25" bay. Useful for mounting your card reader, fan controller, floppy/zip/tape drive, USB header, etc.
Prints without support. All overhangs are 45° except for the screw holes.

Printer Brand:

Ultimaker

Printer:

Ultimaker Original

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Notes: Print slow and cool if you want a pretty result. Beware of lifting corners.

You can fit the 3.5" device to the adapter with one or two screws on each side, or two screws underneath.  
To secure the adapter in the bay, use one self-tapping screw on each side. Regular optical drive bay screws will probably also work OK.
Update Version 2. More rigid. Made the screw holes for the 5.25" mounting a little bit narrower.

"There's always money in the banana stand." Now you too can hint to your family member that "There's always money in the banana stand (click click)" with this banana stand piggy bank. This piggy bank is complete with trash barrel, A-frame sign, bananas, and the famous Bluth's Frozen Banana stand. "I'm an ideas man Michael... I think I proved that with Bluth Banana Stand Piggy Bank". This was a joint effort between me and my wife Scintilla.

All parts should plug together nicely though it depends on the resolution of your printer, this was printed with a Replicator2. You can print all parts except the "stand_bottom.stl" file without supports.   
Download the "StickerSet.gpj" and rename to StickerSet.jpg. This is the image with all the stickers appropriately sized, just print on an 8.5x11" sheet of paper with 100% scaling.   
The barrel was left hollow so you can print a bunch (ha) of bananas and place them in the barrel.

title: Piper Aztec Pilot Air Vent Control Knob

description.text:
This is the round knob that controls the overhead fresh air vent for the pilor and co-pilot in a Piper Aztec F.  May be used on other Piper models too.  This part is no longer available from Piper and is very hard to find elsewhere (and very expensive when you can find it.)  
Openscad source provided for your enjoyment.

The center shaft hole may print a bit small.  If so, just drill it out with a 1/4" bit.  If you have problems getting the dished top to print well, you can turn that off by setting flatTop to 1.  This will create a part with a flat top.  Then just add a set screw and you're done.

Have some sparse food you may not use? Perhaps leftovers from a recipe or maybe you bought to much, simply place the items you want to share in the Food Share basket and share them to a group of friendly neighbors you choose. Your neighbors will be notified and sent images, quantity, and food freshness information of the items you just added. Many cultures and civilizations have used great food to bridge social gaps. In an increasingly technological age, Food Share uses technology to help bring us all to the table for an authentic experience once again.

A friend wanted a set of these tiles so I looked into printing them.  I like that the author made all of them unique, even though that makes for a lot of work manipulating all the print files.  I see a lot of likes of the original tile things, a lot of collections, but very few makes.  Then I downloaded and unzipped them all - 3GB total.  Each tile is commonly 100MB, and that just didn't sound right.  So I ran each file through Netfabb, and that reduced each file size by about 80%.  The repaired files are collected here in their respective .zip's.  They should be much easier to download and manipulate in your slicer.  I've made no changes to the original tiles,  all credit to the original author.

The Beaver Creek region of Idaho constructed using 1 arcsecond resolution SRTM data from the Space Shuttle (about 1.9 million polygons). This map was made using a new and, as yet, unreleased version of SRTM2STL. The source code for creating files at 3 arcsecond resolution is available up on github under the GNU license. Go to github and search for SRTM2STL.

You may want to print this to be relatively small. I used to get warping using PLA and it got bad when I try to print Raised Relief Maps that are big. Now that I have a heated bed, I get much better results.

Making a cube in OpenScad takes just one line of code. Making it nicer (with rounded corners) takes... 40 lines of code!
But hey, the good thing about OpenScad is that once someone makes a library, everything becomes trivial.
So now, making tidy iPhonesque shapes requires just a line of code:
roundCornersCube(10,5,2,1);

You have several options to use this library:
a) Open the .scad file, copy its content and paste it in your script
b) Include the file in your script with any of these commands:
include<"roundCornersCube.stl">
use<"roundCornersCube">
For this option, the library file should be in the same folder as your script.
c) Download the file and copy it in /usr/local/share/openscad/libraries (at least for Ubuntu) Then add it using:
use Calling it:
roundCornersCube(x,y,z,r) Where:
  • x = Xdir width
  • y = Ydir width
  • z = Height of the cube

  • r = Rounding radious

    Example: roundCornerCube(10,10,2,1);
    *Some times it's needed to use F6 to see good results!

    • Preview of the code: http://codeviewer.org/view/code:1b36

comments.text: I updated this library to allow you to select the axis to round edges on.

author: Grue

description.text: Twisty Pawn Chess Piece

I had gotten a bunch of ColorFabb samples to use and I wanted an easy way to load up the 50g samples of filament onto a spool without laborous winding. Basically, remove the side, drop in the hoop of filament, hook the tail end, screw the side back on. You may need to tighten or loosen the coil to make it fit the spool. At least that's far easier than rewinding the filament.  
The center is for a 8mm rod. I've enclosed CAD sources for those that want to alter it for other rod sizes. It could use some more work anyway but I might call this good enough for now.

You'll want M3 flat head screws, 5mm or longer.  
Designed for build with 0.5mm extrusion line widths, which is good with 0.4mm and 0.35mm nozzles.  
You shouldn't need supports but you'll want to be able to do 25mm bridges.  
I suggest two perimeters (any more and your slicer might give you trouble) and 4-6 top and bottom layers.  
I've made this thin and light, so it's very sparing of materials. It should be less than 50g of material consumed. However, if built well, it should be durable.

author: Grue

description.text: This is a replacement for the part of Bender articulated (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:758305) named Link18. It includes a hole suitable for running an elastic cord (or wire) through, in order to help the legs better support Bender's weight. I used the type of silvery elastic cord commonly used to tie small Christmas presents, available at any craft store (and most dollar stores). Thicker 2mm elastic cord will also fit through the holes with a little more effort. Using elastic cord inside the links in the arms helps them hold a pose better, as well. Print 18 of these. Tie knots in each end, then insert into the top and bottom segments for arms and legs. Update: I've also included a beer bottle without hand-holes for Bender's storage area. It prints well with 0% infill and one shell.

comments.text: What an awesome update! The original joints don't pose all that well so this should do the trick.

description.text: Built our first baby blender and on the first crash, the barbeque skewers that the wing mount rubber bands connect to tore through the 9mm of foam board that holds them in place. I deigned these to reinforce the foam on future builds and they also are being used to repair the current one. Make sure you print at a high resolution, supports aren't necessary, and I recommend waiting to add the hole for the skewer until after these are glued in place as to get the placement perfect. Depending on how deep your cut is on the rear, it may or may not line up perfectly. These were designed from a scratch build kit, not a laser cut kit.

L'"Aspi", aspo in italiano, è lo strumento che veniva usato per avvolgere il filo di lana in matassa. La cassa del''aspi" veniva riempita d'acqua e il gomitolo di lana grezza immerso nell'acqua. Il filo veniva svolto bagnato dal gomitolo e riavvolto sull'aspi per dare al filo la forma di matassa.
Sull'aspi si avvolgevano più matasse che, al termine, venivano sfilate dall'aspi e messe ad asciugare o immerse in pentoloni bollenti con del colorante naturale. Tutti i colori venivano derivati da tinture di origine vegetale. L '"Aspi" reel in Italian, is the tool that was used to wrap the wool yarn in hank. The case of the reel was filled with water and a ball of raw wool into water. The wire was carried out by the wet ball and rewound sull'aspi to give the shape of the coil wire.
Of reels they could be wrapped more coils which, terminated, were parades dall'aspi and left to dry or immersed in boiling pots with the natural dye. All colors were derived from dyes of plant origin.
